I got the error too, and I am able to reliably reproduce the bug.
The heart of the issue lies in MudFocusTrap.razor.cs OnAfterRenderAsync.

In short, if you have pressed "Ok" (closed) on the dialog quickly enough and lucky enough for the race condition to occur, then InitializeFocusAsync will be called after disposal, causing the crash. By lucky enough to occur, it needs to be still in OnAfterRenderAsync for the firstRender. So most likely it will only occur on slower machines, which is why most people only see it in production once published etc... There already is a `if (_disposed) return;` at the top of the method before the saving of focus, but this is not enough.
The fix is extremely simple, there needs to be another `if (_disposed) return; ` before the second part of OnAfterRenderAsync. This is because we are awaiting SaveFocusAsync, and when the method continues, disposal could have already happened.

To reproduce this reliably, you can modify OnAfterRenderAsync and put a delay in.

```
 protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
 {
     await base.OnAfterRenderAsync(firstRender);

     if (_disposed) return;
     if (firstRender)
     {
         await SaveFocusAsync();
     }

     Debug.WriteLine("Delay by 3 seconds to test issue");
     await Task.Delay(3000);

     if (!_initialized)
     {
         await InitializeFocusAsync();
     }
 }
```

Then simply open a dialog, and press Ok straight away to close it. Then wait a second or two, and the server will crash.

To fix, it's as simple as:
```
protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
{
    await base.OnAfterRenderAsync(firstRender);

    if (_disposed) return;
    if (firstRender)
    {
        await SaveFocusAsync();
    }

    // need to check _disposed again because it could have changed during await
    if (_disposed) return;
    if (!_initialized)
    {
        await InitializeFocusAsync();
    }
}
```

Do I submit code for this, or is it handled by the team?

